{"ts": "2026-04-21T19:16:29Z", "event": "clarify_critic", "feature": "build-cortex-cli-skeleton-with-uv-tool-install-entry-point", "findings": ["Intent clarity rated HIGH claims every deliverable is named, but the source hedges the CLI framework choice — \"probably click or typer, argparse is the floor\" — leaving a load-bearing implementation decision unresolved.", "Intent clarity cites Epic research DR-1, but the ticket body actually cites DR-4 and DR-5; the assessment is importing external context and then crediting the ticket for clarity it does not explicitly contain.", "Scope boundedness rated HIGH because Scope/Out-of-Scope sections exist, but the Scope section does not specify package layout, package/module names, per-subcommand --help text, exit-code conventions, version subcommand, or shell-completion hooks — calling skeleton inherently limiting is an assertion.", "Requirements alignment PARTIAL is justified by DR-8 and DR-10 references that do not appear in the ticket body; the project.md out-of-scope clause for Published packages is conflict, and the reconciliation cited is not claimed by the ticket itself.", "Complexity rated simple ignores the source-surfaced sharp edges — uv#9518 and uv tool update-shell PATH setup — that turn build-system declarations from mechanical into debugging sessions; the complexity rating does not engage with this caveat.", "Criticality rated high via the lifecycle default (skill/lifecycle/hook/workflow changes), but this is net-new packaging infrastructure, not a change to existing skills/hooks/workflows; the mapping from default phrasing to this class of change is not justified."], "dispositions": {"apply": 4, "dismiss": 2, "ask": 0}, "applied_fixes": ["Added CLI framework choice (click vs typer vs argparse) to research open questions rather than downgrade Intent clarity — argparse floor means any choice satisfies the deliverable, but research must decide.", "Corrected the DR references in the Intent clarity rationale to cite DR-4 and DR-5 as the ticket does, removing the DR-1 attribution.", "Stripped DR-8 and DR-10 references from the Requirements alignment rationale; partial justified solely from the ticket body plus current requirements/project.md text.", "Revised complexity from simple to complex — introduces a new packaging pattern (first Python CLI package in this repo), has a judgment call on CLI framework, 4+ files touched, and when in doubt prefer complex per the dimensions table."], "dismissals": [{"finding_index": 2, "rationale": "The ticket body's Scope section enumerates five in-scope bullets exhaustively: build-system declaration, entry point, subcommand scaffolding with not-yet-implemented placeholders, uv tool install -e verification, and the uv run constraint documentation. Items the critic lists as omitted (shell completion, --version subcommand, per-subcommand --help specifics, exit-code conventions, src vs flat layout, module name) are not scope gaps — layout and module name are implementation details for research, and the others are not in Scope because they are not listed."}, {"finding_index": 5, "rationale": "The criticality high tier explicitly covers \"significant impact or hard to reverse, OR any change to shared skills / workflow infrastructure / overnight runner / hooks that other capabilities depend on.\" The ticket body verbatim states \"Every other ticket in this epic depends on the cortex CLI existing — it owns the runner, dashboard, MCP server, setup subcommand, and scaffolder.\" That is the shared-infrastructure clause applied literally; the lifecycle default phrasing is non-exhaustive and the high tier holds."}], "status": "ok"}
